needle.text: The mind, accustomed to pursuing distinct ideas, exhibits restless activity even when such ideas are obtained. For the actions of consciousness cease not with mere possession of complex ideas, but seek to discern new relations among them.

response: The mind, even after obtaining distinct complex ideas, continues to be restless, seeking to discover new relationships among them.

response: The mind, after receiving ideas, has the power to repeat, compare, and unite them, creating new complex ideas. It also actively exercises its discerning faculties, comparing ideas and composing them into new combinations. This activity includes processes like remembrance, discerning, comparing, compounding, naming, and abstracting. The mind does not cease its activity with the mere possession of complex ideas, but continues to seek out new relations among them.

response: The mind, once it has simple ideas, can repeat, compare, and unite them to form new complex ideas. It can also discern and distinguish between ideas, compound them, enlarge them, abstract them, and learn to use words to signify them. It can fix ideas in memory through attention, repetition, pleasure, and pain. It can suspend the satisfaction of desires to examine the good or evil of an action, and its intentions and study involve earnestly fixing its view on an idea and considering it from all sides.
